    Date: Sat, 28 Nov 87 11:30:14 -0500 (EST)
    From: "Craig F. Everhart" &lt;cfe+@andrew.cmu.edu&gt;

    Here's another nit to consider when planning user@domain &lt;=&gt; user.domain 
    equivalences.
I'm confused.  The domain system already has the user@domain ==
user.domain equivalence.  What I'm advocating is breaking the
equivalence.
    The RFC822 syntax for mailboxes is at root local-part@domain, 
    and what's allowed as a local-part is a superset of what's allowed as an 
    RFC821 or RFC883 domain.  If I'm to support user.domain naming via the 
    nameserver system, I'd like to allow an address like ``cfe+.andrew.cmu.edu''.
I don't see any reason to disallow that.  There may be reasons why you
would prefer something better.  This gets into the distinction between
user objects and login IDs.  The user object that represents you need
not have the same terminal label as the login IDs you have on various
systems.  For example, you might have the various login IDs of Craig,
craig, cfe, cfe+, ceverhart, etc.  The name of your user object, which I
claim is what wants to appear as the user.domain syntax address, might
have some relation to one of these, but need not.  It might be
CFEverhart.cmu.edu, for example, and mail to that address might get
delivered to cfe+@andrew.cmu.edu.

    Rationalizing the syntax for ``domain,'' between RFC821 and RFC822 and the 
    real world (in which ``foo.bar.[128.2.202.12].cmu.edu'' probably doesn't make 
    much sense) might be a reasonable goal for a mail naming revision.

Agreed.

